e></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE00380X%2F1"><gtr:id>DF5D884A-945D-4100-91E2-704D57B76528</gtr:id><gtr:title>Collective Action in a Deeply Divided Society: the Civil Rights Movement in Northern Ireland</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E00380X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research project will utilise the Northern Ireland Civil Rights Movement (mid 1960s ? early 1970s) as a case study, to question the interactive development processes of social movements and their short-term outcomes and long-term legacies. Addressing some of the key issues recently highlighted by the literature on collective action, it intends to move beyond the imbalance of movement-centric explanations, and tries to understand the dynamic direct and indirect interactions between different actors in the Northern Ireland political system (the Civil Rights Movement, the Unionist establishment, the Loyalist countermovement, Northern Ireland political parties, regional mass media). Focusing on a deeply divided society, such as Northern Ireland, this research broadens the comparative range of case studies in the field of social movements and enhances our awareness of collective action in relation on how establishment repressive measures, in determinate societies, might increase individuals? involvement in social movement activities. This research project can be seen also as a significant step towards making the Northern Ireland historical reconstruction more scholarly and detached from ideological conflicts.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePo